entries.title: Best text-to-speech software of 2025
entries.snippet:
This document from TechRadar (dated September 29, 2025) presents a comprehensive guide to the best text-to-speech (TTS) software of 2025. It emphasizes the growing importance of TTS for accessibility, productivity, and content creation, particularly in media like YouTube and podcasting.

The top picks include:

1. **NaturalReader** – Best overall for personal/home use, offering 56 voices across 9 languages and cloud-based access.
2. **Murf** – Best for realistic AI voices, ideal for e-learning and presentations, with advanced editing and voice-changing tools.
3. **Amazon Polly** – Best for developers, offering easy API integration and broad language support.
4. **Play.ht** – Best for podcasting, providing nearly 600 voices in over 60 languages, with options tailored for commercial use.
5. **Voice Dream Reader** – Best for Mac and iOS users, offering 186 voices in 30 languages and compatibility with multiple cloud services.

The article also explains the difference between web-based TTS services and desktop software, discusses subscription models, and offers advice for integrating TTS into business workflows. Each software was rigorously tested based on performance, usability, voice quality, and pricing.

entries.title: Amazon plays catch-up with new Nova AI models to generate voices and video
entries.snippet:
Amazon has unveiled new AI innovations aimed at competing with leading technologies like Gemini Live and OpenAI’s Advanced Voice Mode. The highlight is the Nova Sonic voice model, designed for real-time speech processing and natural conversational interactions. Unlike traditional systems that rely on separate components for speech recognition, text conversion, and voice generation, Nova Sonic employs a unified model architecture, enabling more fluid and context-aware responses. It also improves detection of tone for more natural communication. Available on Amazon’s Bedrock developer platform, Nova Sonic targets applications in customer service, healthcare, travel, and education, and is already partially integrated into the new Alexa Plus assistant.

In addition to voice AI, Amazon released Nova Reel 1.1, an update focused on video generation. This upgrade enhances video quality and reduces latency compared to its predecessor. Nova Reel 1.1 can maintain consistent visual styles across several short video segments, allowing creation of cohesive videos up to two minutes long. These developments reflect Amazon’s push to advance in the competitive AI space.

Google Vids can now generate AI voiceovers for your videos
entries.snippet:
Google Vids, a new service within Google Workspace, enhances its video and presentation creation tools by introducing AI-generated voiceovers. Designed primarily for work and educational settings, Google Vids uses AI and Gemini tools to produce content like slideshows and presentations. Previously, users could generate a voiceover script via the “Help me Create” feature. Now, the platform also allows AI to narrate these scripts, making it a more dynamic content creation tool.

Users can customize their voiceovers by selecting different tones, pitch levels, and voice types, and they can edit both the script and the voiceover post-generation. This new functionality is exclusive to paid Google Workspace plans and began rolling out on March 20, 2025, though it may take up to 15 days to become available to all users.

entries.title: Piotr Dabkowski
entries.snippet:
ElevenLabs, a rapidly growing AI startup co-founded by Polish entrepreneurs Piotr Dabkowski and Mateusz Staniszewski, has developed a state-of-the-art voice cloning technology. This tool allows users to generate lifelike voices from short audio samples and supports speech synthesis in 29 languages, making it highly useful for dubbing and voiceover applications. The company, just two years old, is already valued at $1.1 billion and has secured $80 million in funding from investors like Andreessen Horowitz. Major clients include HarperCollins, TIME, and the Washington Post.

The model stands out for its high quality, low latency, and robustness. Dabkowski notes that the technology is approaching a "quality ceiling," where AI-generated voices are indistinguishable from real human ones, raising ethical and security concerns. To address this, ElevenLabs has built-in safeguards such as credit card verification for access, audio generation tracking, and a speech classifier to detect AI-generated content. The company also participates in the U.S. AI Safety Institute's Consortium. Despite these efforts, some users have bypassed protections, emphasizing the ongoing challenge of preventing misuse in the rapidly evolving landscape of generative AI.

entries.title: Adobe's New Audio Software Eerily Mimics Human Speech
entries.snippet:
Adobe is developing a groundbreaking audio software called Project VoCo, which was showcased at the MAX conference. The software functions like an audio version of Photoshop, allowing users to edit, synthesize, and generate speech with remarkable realism. By analyzing just 20 minutes of recorded speech, Project VoCo can mimic a person's voice to produce entirely new words and sentences that sound convincingly natural. Adobe explained that the tool is particularly useful for altering or correcting voiceovers, narration, and dialogue — users simply type in the desired change, and the algorithm recreates the audio seamlessly in the original speaker’s voice.

Despite its potential, Project VoCo raises ethical concerns, especially in light of past controversies involving digital image manipulation. The software has not been released commercially, and Adobe has not disclosed any future plans for its release. Its capabilities, while impressive, underscore the importance of responsible use and the need for safeguards against misuse.

entries.title: OpenAI reveals Voice Engine, but won't yet publicly release the risky AI voice-cloning technology
entries.snippet: OpenAI has unveiled a new technology called Voice Engine, which can clone a person's voice using just 15 seconds of recorded audio. Despite demonstrating its capabilities, OpenAI has chosen not to publicly release the technology due to concerns over potential misuse, particularly during an election year. The company highlighted the risks of producing speech that imitates real people and cited ethical concerns, especially in light of recent incidents involving AI-generated robocalls mimicking political figures. Voice Engine will be tested with early users under strict guidelines: voices must not be used to impersonate individuals without consent, and all AI-generated voices must be disclosed. This move aligns with OpenAI's cautious release strategy previously seen with its video generator, Sora. OpenAI has also filed a trademark for Voice Engine and may enter the broader market of speech recognition and digital voice assistants, potentially positioning itself against competitors like Amazon's Alexa. The Associated Press has a licensing and technology agreement with OpenAI.
